Keybindings can be changed in th' {(Menu.Options.5):Options Menu}.

Fer more binds, see th' {(Menu.Options.5):Options Menu}.

{# Movement}

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Directional movement:} {BINDINGS:GameMoveUp} (up), {BINDINGS:GameMoveLeft} (left), {BINDINGS:GameMoveDown} (down), {BINDINGS:GameMoveRight} (right)

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Move towards mouse:} {BINDINGS:GameMoveDirection}

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Move t' th' tile under th' mouse:} {BINDINGS:GameMoveToTile}

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Skip/pass a turn:} {BINDINGS:GameIdle} or {BINDINGS:GameMoveDirection} (with yer mouse over yer character).

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Facin' a direction without movin':} {BINDINGS:GameFaceDirection} and yer character will face towards yer mouse (thar be correspondin' facin' binds fer all directions as well).

If thar be too much or too little delay between turnin' a direction and movin', ye can fine-tune it in th' {(Menu.Options.3):Options Menu}.

{# Actions}

Interactin' through th' world be done mostly through th' {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):actions} menu, opened usin' {BINDINGS:GameActions}.

{# Usin' Items}

See {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):Actions} and {(Menu.HelpArticle.Quickslots):Quickslots}.

{# Item Management}

{_Droppin' items_}

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Drop an item:} {BINDINGS:GameItemDrop} (when th' mouse be over th' item), or use th' {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):"Drop" action} on th' item. 

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Drop all o' a type o' item:} {BINDINGS:GameItemDropAll} (when th' mouse be over th' type o' item t' drop), or use th' {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):"Drop All" action}.

If thar be a tile in th' way o' droppin' an item, by default nothin' will happen. Ye may change this functionality in th' "Drop Location" settin', available in th' {(Menu.Options.3):Options Menu} and th' Quick Settings dialog.

{_Movin' items_}

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Quickly movin' items between containers:} {BINDINGS:GameItemQuickMove} (when th' mouse be over th' item)

{#--TEXT-SECONDARY:Quickly movin' all o' th' same type o' item between containers:} {BINDINGS:GameItemQuickMoveAll} (when th' mouse be over th' type o' item)

Quick-movin' items works with yer open container dialog, or, if thar be no container dialog open, th' container yer character be facin'.

{# More Information}

Hoverin' over elements on screen will typically reveal more information, usually in a tooltip. Some examples include items in dialogs, and doodads, creatures, and items in th' world. Items in th' craftin' dialog will highlight th' items that will be used when they be crafted.

Tooltips fer tiles in th' world can be disabled. When this be th' case, ye can still get information about th' tile ye be hoverin' over with {BINDINGS:GameInspect}.

quickslots:
{(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):Openin' an item's menu t' perform actions} can be tiresome. Quickslots be fer usin' an action on an item with th' press o' a bind.

{# Quickslottin' an Item}

Ye can drag some godforsaken item into one o' yer nine quickslots t' quickslot th' item in that slot. Ye can also use any o' th' quickslot binds t' toggle th' item bein' quickslotted t' th' slot o' th' bind ye press. Alternatively, ye can use th' {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):"Add t' Quickslot" action} t' add it t' an open quickslot.

{# Usin' a Quickslotted Item}

By default, pressin' th' bind fer a quickslot will perform th' default {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):action} fer th' item in that slot; th' action depends on what kind o' item it be. 

Ye can change th' action t' perform fer a quickslot item by openin' th' actions menu ({BINDINGS:GameItemMenu}), and clickin' th' x icon next t' th' preferred action, turnin' it into a √.

{# Removin' a Quickslotted Item}

Thar be two binds provided fer removin' items from quickslots. Ye can press {BINDINGS:GameQuickSlotClear} t' clear th' hovered item from its quickslot, or t' clear th' hovered quickslot. Ye can also press any o' th' quickslot binds t' toggle th' hovered item bein' quickslotted t' that slot.

attackingDamage:
{_Auto Attack_}
By default, ye will attack creatures (who be not tamed) by walkin' into them. Ye can disable this feature by either turnin' off th' Auto Attack option in th' Options menu or Quick Settings ({BINDINGS:DialogOptions}) dialog. Ye will also not automatically attack if ye have both o' yer hands disabled fer use. While either o' these be true, ye sometimes may swap positions with creatures if they be small enough. Not all creatures, includin' bigger creatures, will allow ye t' swap positions with them.

{_Equipment & Hand Usage_}
Ye can enable and disable each {(Menu.HelpArticle.HeldItems):hand} fer use when attackin' by selectin' th' checkboxes underneath th' Equipment dialog or by usin' th' {BINDINGS:GameHandToggleLeft} and {BINDINGS:GameHandToggleRight} binds fer each hand. If no equipment be equipped in yer hands, ye will use yer fist. If both hands be selected fer use, ye will take turns usin' each hand, each attack.

{_Damage Types_}
Thar be four damage types: Piercin', Slashin', Blunt, and Fire. These damage types be applied t' every weapon and creature. They exist as vulnerabilities and resistances on equipment and creatures. Hoverin' over weapons and equipment items will reveal these values. By hoverin' over creatures, yer skill in Anatomy will give ye an idea o' what damage types th' creature be vulnerable or resistant to. Th' accuracy o' this readout will improve as yer skill in Anatomy increases.

{_Effectiveness_}
If a weapon has multiple damage types, it will use both o' them on each hit. Each value in a resistance will reduce th' damage by one, and each vulnerability will increase it by one. As an example:

Ye hit a scorpion with a wooden sword that deals 3 blunt/piercin' damage. Scorpions have a resistance o' 1 against piercin' and a vulnerability o' 2 against blunt with a base defense o' 2. Th' scorpion would take 2 damage (3 - 2 - 1 + 2) in this scenario when other factors like skills be not applied.

Ye can review yer current vulnerabilities and resistances by hoverin' over th' defense numbers next t' th' shield icon by yer stats.

{_Parryin'_}
By equippin' two weapons, two shields, or a combination in between each hand, ye will begin t' parry automatically. While parryin', yer base defense will raise and can sometimes parry incomin' attacks from creatures, mitigatin' some damage. This increased defense and damage mitigation chance be dependent on yer parryin' skill. Ye can review these values by hoverin' over th' defense numbers next t' th' shield icon by yer stats. Th' parryin' skill will raise as ye engage in combat with both hands equipped.

{_Tactics_}
Tactics will increase th' damage ye can perform when attackin'. Ye can review this value by hoverin' over th' attack numbers next t' th' sword icon by yer stats. Th' tactics skill will raise as ye engage in combat.

{_Attackin' Merchants_}
By default, when walkin' into {(Menu.HelpArticle.Merchants):merchants}, ye will not attack them, but instead, trade with them. Ye have t' specifically attack them t' engage in combat. Ye can do this through th' action menu, by choosin' th' "Attack" action, or by choosin' th' "Attack" action on an individual item by openin' th' item's menu. Damagin' them in other ways will also cause them t' become hostile.

restingSleeping:
Restin' and sleepin' be different actions and have their own set o' pros and cons.

{_Restin'_}
1. Ye be able t' cancel out o' restin'.
2. Reduces hunger and thirst rate, but not as much as sleepin'.
3. Increases stamina and health regeneration, but not as much as sleepin'.
4. Ye cannot rest while yer stamina be full. Rest will automatically be cancelled once yer stamina be full.
5. Fire sources have no impact on regeneration or rest length.

{_Sleepin'_}
1. Ye cannot cancel out o' sleepin', potentially leadin' t' oversleepin' or other dangers.
2. Reduces hunger and thirst rate more so than restin'.
3. Increases stamina and health regeneration more so than restin'.
4. Ye can sleep indefinitely regardless o' stamina value.
5. Fire sources (lit campfires, lit furnaces, coolin' lava, etc.) will produce better stamina and health regeneration as well as increase th' amount o' turns ye can sleep in one {(Menu.HelpArticle.Actions):action}.

{_Items & Doodads_}
By usin' a beddin' item or {(Menu.HelpArticle.Doodads):doodad} (like a placed bedroll) ye will receive better stamina and health regeneration. Restin' or sleepin' on th' ground will produce th' worst regenerative effects. A message will appear warnin' ye o' this effect.

{_Creatures_}
Ye will not be able t' rest or sleep effectively while untamed creatures be nearby. If they be breakin' doodads (like doors and walls) within a radius o' up t' 5 tiles away, ye may wake up. If they be up t' 3 tiles away, ye may also wake up from hearin' them stirrin'.

{_Terrain_}
Restin' or sleepin' on certain terrain will decrease th' maximum amount o' turns ye can rest or sleep in one action. This includes terrain like water, snow, etc. A message will appear warnin' ye o' this effect.

{_Campin'_}
Th' higher yer campin' skill, th' higher th' maximum amount o' turns ye can rest or sleep in one action.

{_Darkness_}
Darkness in th' form o' nighttime or caves will increase th' amount o' turns ye can rest or sleep in one action.

{_Multiplayer & Real-time_}
Restin' and sleepin' work differently when playin' a multiplayer game or settin' th' mode t' "real-time" turns, in that performin' th' rest/sleep actions will no longer progress time (or pass turns). Its use be shifted towards a regenerative role exclusively in these modes.

